WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.960 --> 00:00:05.440
Professor Robert
Shiller: I wanted first to

00:00:05.440 --> 00:00:09.488
just think back a little bit
about the lecture we got from

00:00:09.488 --> 00:00:12.816
Steve Schwarzman on Friday.
Before he came,

00:00:12.816 --> 00:00:17.249
I talked with him in my office
and I had the audacity to ask

00:00:17.249 --> 00:00:21.982
him if he thought there was any
chance that his fortune was just

00:00:21.982 --> 00:00:26.137
due to luck.
I said, why we have this

00:00:26.137 --> 00:00:32.852
efficient markets theory in
finance that says that nobody

00:00:32.852 --> 00:00:37.570
can beat the market.
So, what do you think he said?

00:00:37.570 --> 00:00:43.616
Well, obviously he believes in
himself, but I'm inclined to

00:00:43.616 --> 00:00:50.043
believe in him also.
Efficient markets theory never

00:00:50.043 --> 00:00:53.977
sounded right;
one thing about efficient

00:00:53.977 --> 00:00:58.383
markets theory that has always
bothered me is this idea that

00:00:58.383 --> 00:01:02.640
the so-called "smart money" sets
prices in the market.

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:07.469
The thing that bothers me about
it is, who is the "smart money,"

00:01:07.469 --> 00:01:09.659
anyway?
It's as if it's all or nothing

00:01:09.659 --> 00:01:11.551
thing;
there's the smart money and

00:01:11.551 --> 00:01:14.519
then it's the dumb money and the
smart money rules.

00:01:14.519 --> 00:01:18.100
Aren't there all different
gradations of intelligence and

00:01:18.100 --> 00:01:21.158
insight?
It's not like--why should there

00:01:21.158 --> 00:01:23.810
be just one level of smart
money?

00:01:23.810 --> 00:01:29.077
So, I think he probably
exemplifies a higher level of

00:01:29.077 --> 00:01:33.779
smart money than smart.
I think a lot of mistakes

00:01:33.779 --> 00:01:38.553
people make in judging financial
markets is being easily

00:01:38.553 --> 00:01:43.240
impressed by someone's
stockbroker or someone's analyst

00:01:43.240 --> 00:01:47.060
who seems very smart and is very
smart,

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:50.420
but may not be enough to
outsmart the markets.

00:01:50.420 --> 00:01:55.385
That's the lesson of
efficiency, especially when

00:01:55.385 --> 00:01:59.542
you're young.
I think you may not realize how

00:01:59.542 --> 00:02:04.106
many smart people there are in
the world, so when you're

00:02:04.106 --> 00:02:09.084
dealing in a--trying to win in
financial markets--you have to

00:02:09.084 --> 00:02:13.980
take account of who is really
out there and how much insight

00:02:13.980 --> 00:02:19.539
and effort and research are they
putting into their trading.

00:02:19.539 --> 00:02:22.830
Do you really think you can
beat that?

00:02:22.830 --> 00:02:26.189
That's the lesson of efficient
markets.

00:02:26.189 --> 00:02:30.830
I don't think the lesson is
that you can't--it's impossible

00:02:30.830 --> 00:02:34.990
for anyone no matter how smart
to beat the market.

00:02:34.990 --> 00:02:37.807
Now of course,
Albert Einstein never made any

00:02:37.807 --> 00:02:40.968
money in the stock market.
In fact, TIAA-CREF,

00:02:40.968 --> 00:02:44.138
the pension fund,
had an ad campaign in which

00:02:44.138 --> 00:02:48.172
they pointed that Albert
Einstein left all of his pension

00:02:48.172 --> 00:02:52.457
investing to TIAA-CREF.
He was a professor and they're

00:02:52.457 --> 00:02:57.418
a pension fund for professors.
Einstein didn't think he could

00:02:57.418 --> 00:03:01.522
beat the market and Mr.
Schwarzman very candidly

00:03:01.522 --> 00:03:06.760
pointed out that he didn't have
the greatest math scores.

00:03:06.760 --> 00:03:11.089
Isn't that how he put it?
He said he was no math genius

00:03:11.089 --> 00:03:17.313
and you think finance requires a
lot of math, but I think that

00:03:17.313 --> 00:03:22.110
it's something about practical
intelligence.

00:03:22.110 --> 00:03:25.875
Psychologists have talked about
different kinds of

00:03:25.875 --> 00:03:30.025
intelligence--this is all
supposed to be coming up here

00:03:30.025 --> 00:03:33.421
now.
At least we're seeing something

00:03:33.421 --> 00:03:35.216
now.
This is why I don't like

00:03:35.216 --> 00:03:46.310
Powerpoint, actually;
this kind of thing happens it

00:03:46.310 --> 00:03:55.530
always seems to happen.
So, that's it.

00:03:55.530 --> 00:04:04.328
I'm not going to use this for a
few minutes.--But,

00:04:04.328 --> 00:04:12.229
remember Carl Icahn,
when he talked to us,

00:04:12.229 --> 00:04:16.283
said something about he always
just had some--he was always

00:04:16.283 --> 00:04:21.928
just good at making money.
I think that there are separate

00:04:21.928 --> 00:04:24.024
talents.
I mean, some people love

00:04:24.024 --> 00:04:26.544
markets and they like to think
about them and figure out how

00:04:26.544 --> 00:04:29.363
they work.
If they have the right kind of

00:04:29.363 --> 00:04:33.589
intelligence and the right kind
of spirit to do the work,

00:04:33.589 --> 00:04:36.910
they ought to be able to beat
the market.

00:04:36.910 --> 00:04:41.053
I've talked to Icahn a number
of times and I have the idea

00:04:41.053 --> 00:04:45.269
that he's a very down-to-earth,
solid, inquisitive sort;

00:04:45.269 --> 00:04:47.170
he wants to know what's going
on.

00:04:47.170 --> 00:04:50.689
When I've talked to him,
sometimes he'll ask the same

00:04:50.689 --> 00:04:53.293
question of me;
he's trying to get information

00:04:53.293 --> 00:04:55.538
from me.
He asks the same question from

00:04:55.538 --> 00:04:58.975
me three different ways because
apparently my answer isn't

00:04:58.975 --> 00:05:02.774
satisfactory and he must think I
might know something because he

00:05:02.774 --> 00:05:06.184
keeps asking.
But, I think that's the kind of

00:05:06.184 --> 00:05:10.982
persistence--certain personality
traits--persistence at trying to

00:05:10.982 --> 00:05:15.105
figure out what really makes
things work is important in

00:05:15.105 --> 00:05:18.497
these markets.
I think it's just relish or

00:05:18.497 --> 00:05:22.795
inclination to keep thinking
about them, so maybe that's why

00:05:22.795 --> 00:05:25.709
I went into economics as a
professor.

00:05:25.709 --> 00:05:28.902
I don't know that I really was
someone who wants to watch the

00:05:28.902 --> 00:05:32.318
markets all day;
so, you have to judge your own

00:05:32.318 --> 00:05:37.063
interests.
Anyway, it was very nice that

00:05:37.063 --> 00:05:44.352
we got--that Steve Schwarzman
came and told us about his

00:05:44.352 --> 00:05:51.399
life's work.
Anyway, I want to talk today

00:05:51.399 --> 00:05:56.497
about futures.
One more thing I wanted to say

00:05:56.497 --> 00:05:58.643
about Schwarzman.
At one point,

00:05:58.643 --> 00:06:01.663
he said very confidently,
I thought--and I don't know if

00:06:01.663 --> 00:06:05.012
you heard this right--that this
current financial crisis ought

00:06:05.012 --> 00:06:08.637
to be over in a year.
He said something--and maybe it

00:06:08.637 --> 00:06:12.040
was a little vague--about
investing in distressed

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:16.435
securities now as an opportunity
because I think he pointed out

00:06:16.435 --> 00:06:20.971
that AAA mortgage securities are
selling for eighty some cents on

00:06:20.971 --> 00:06:24.019
the dollar and it can't be that
bad.

00:06:24.019 --> 00:06:27.627
This is the same theme that we
got from David Swensen and I've

00:06:27.627 --> 00:06:30.939
heard it from others--that
that's the opportunity now.

00:06:30.939 --> 00:06:34.217
When I hear Steve Schwarzman
proclaiming that he thinks

00:06:34.217 --> 00:06:37.009
this--I thought he said
something like that,

00:06:37.009 --> 00:06:40.660
that this business crisis will
be over before long.

00:06:40.660 --> 00:06:43.438
It made me wonder,
do I know more than he does

00:06:43.438 --> 00:06:47.265
about that sort of thing because
I don't think it's going to be

00:06:47.265 --> 00:06:49.408
over soon?
Then it gets back to,

00:06:49.408 --> 00:06:52.940
I think, you have to put all
these people in perspective;

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:55.290
there are so many different
kinds of expertise.

00:06:55.290 --> 00:06:59.804
When you listen to someone you
always have to ask,

00:06:59.804 --> 00:07:04.780
well what does he or she know
that is specific to their

00:07:04.780 --> 00:07:08.280
expertise?
I don't think Schwarzman is a

00:07:08.280 --> 00:07:11.481
macroeconomist,
so I don't want to say he's

00:07:11.481 --> 00:07:17.264
wrong, but he might be wrong.
The good thing is to listen to

00:07:17.264 --> 00:07:23.620
everyone and not accept that
anyone has the whole truth.

00:07:23.620 --> 00:07:27.560
Anyway, I want to get on to
futures markets.

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:33.905
That is a very important topic
in finance and the important

00:07:33.905 --> 00:07:39.533
thing to understand is,
when I put an "s" on the end

00:07:39.533 --> 00:07:45.319
"futures," that refers to a
marketplace with a particular

00:07:45.319 --> 00:07:50.670
characteristic,
as traded on a number of

00:07:50.670 --> 00:07:54.779
exchanges.
Notably, in the U.S.

00:07:54.779 --> 00:08:01.934
the biggest exchange for
futures is the Chicago

00:08:01.934 --> 00:08:09.089
Mercantile Exchange,
which just merged with The

00:08:09.089 --> 00:08:19.199
Chicago Board of Trade and they
are now called the CME Group.

00:08:19.199 --> 00:08:22.490
Futures, since it has its
origin in agriculture,

00:08:22.490 --> 00:08:25.990
is a Chicago thing rather than
a New York thing.

00:08:25.990 --> 00:08:31.034
Chicago is the "second city,"
or it was the second biggest

00:08:31.034 --> 00:08:36.167
city, hog-butcher to the world,
farmers' marketplace in the

00:08:36.167 --> 00:08:38.847
Midwest;
so, futures in the United

00:08:38.847 --> 00:08:40.270
States started there.

00:08:45.679 --> 00:08:49.769
Actually, futures didn't start
in Chicago;

00:08:49.769 --> 00:09:06.903
it started in Japan on an
island in Osaka called Dojima in

00:09:06.903 --> 00:09:14.116
the 1600s.
I'm sorry, did I--yeah it was

00:09:14.116 --> 00:09:21.330
the 1600s--1673 is the date for
the first futures market.

00:09:21.330 --> 00:09:28.341
I was just in Osaka again a few
months ago and I again asked,

00:09:28.341 --> 00:09:35.470
can I please see Dojima because
it's such a historic place.

00:09:35.470 --> 00:09:37.791
Again they said,
there's nothing to see there,

00:09:37.791 --> 00:09:40.009
it's all--anything from long
ago is gone.

00:09:40.009 --> 00:09:43.169
That was where these markets
started.

00:09:43.169 --> 00:09:48.432
Let's go back--and I'm not sure
how well-developed it was in

00:09:48.432 --> 00:09:54.139
1673, but let's say early 1700s
in Dojima--what was happening?

00:09:54.139 --> 00:09:56.429
Well, it was the rice center
for Japan.

00:09:56.429 --> 00:10:02.375
The people--rice merchants
would bring their rice to Dojima

00:10:02.375 --> 00:10:07.938
and sell them there.
Naturally, as you would expect,

00:10:07.938 --> 00:10:14.129
there were big warehouses for
rice, which would store it;

00:10:14.129 --> 00:10:21.049
it would be a natural thing to
see at the center of trade.

00:10:21.049 --> 00:10:26.309
It was a big and thriving trade
center.

00:10:26.309 --> 00:10:29.439
People, when they buy--so
incidentally,

00:10:29.439 --> 00:10:32.980
let's talk about the
fundamental problem.

00:10:32.980 --> 00:10:38.808
Agricultural commodities like
rice are harvested typically

00:10:38.808 --> 00:10:43.090
once a year.
Actually, I think rice has more

00:10:43.090 --> 00:10:47.320
than one harvest,
but let's just simplify it;

00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:49.299
let's say it's harvested once
per year.

00:10:49.299 --> 00:10:52.648
People depend on it for their
lives, actually,

00:10:52.648 --> 00:10:56.220
because they need the food for
the whole year.

00:10:56.220 --> 00:10:58.550
That means there's a storage
business;

00:10:58.550 --> 00:11:02.529
rice has to be stored;
you have to keep it away from

00:11:02.529 --> 00:11:06.370
moisture and rot and away from
rats and vermin.

00:11:06.370 --> 00:11:12.321
That's a business and it's a
very important business for any

00:11:12.321 --> 00:11:15.103
country.
If it weren't rice,

00:11:15.103 --> 00:11:19.490
it would be some other grain,
which is stored.

00:11:19.490 --> 00:11:23.938
When people buy and sell grain
they know it's--they're thinking

00:11:23.938 --> 00:11:28.172
out at least a year because
that's how long the cycle is for

00:11:28.172 --> 00:11:32.227
one harvest--one cycle.
So, lots of contracts are

00:11:32.227 --> 00:11:36.972
signed to buy and sell rice,
but typically at some future

00:11:36.972 --> 00:11:41.418
date.
We talk about "spot contracts,"

00:11:41.418 --> 00:11:47.740
which means buying and selling
something right now.

00:11:47.740 --> 00:11:51.841
If you show up at the warehouse
and say, I've got my wagons,

00:11:51.841 --> 00:11:55.864
I want to load rice in.
How much do I have to pay to

00:11:55.864 --> 00:11:58.771
get rice?
That price would be called the

00:11:58.771 --> 00:12:01.419
"spot price"--on the spot,
right now.

00:12:01.419 --> 00:12:07.195
But often, you would show up at
the warehouse and you would say,

00:12:07.195 --> 00:12:11.948
I have some trucks,
wagons coming next week or next

00:12:11.948 --> 00:12:16.419
month and I want to arrange now
to buy the rice.

00:12:16.419 --> 00:12:23.055
If you say--if you agree on a
price today for delivery in one

00:12:23.055 --> 00:12:29.360
month, that's called a "forward
contract," not futures.

00:12:29.360 --> 00:12:32.210
There's an important
distinction between forward and

00:12:32.210 --> 00:12:34.590
futures.
A forward contract--let me

00:12:34.590 --> 00:12:38.159
explain what a forward
contract--it's very simple.

00:12:38.159 --> 00:12:43.783
It's a contract between two
parties to exchange something at

00:12:43.783 --> 00:12:49.406
a future date for a price in the
future that's predetermined

00:12:49.406 --> 00:12:51.408
today.
For example,

00:12:51.408 --> 00:12:56.387
a forward contract will be
between a rice merchant and the

00:12:56.387 --> 00:13:01.628
warehouse that in two months I
will come and take delivery of

00:13:01.628 --> 00:13:06.694
so many bushels of rice and then
I will pay such and such a

00:13:06.694 --> 00:13:09.570
price;
that's a forward contract.

00:13:09.570 --> 00:13:12.945
Before 1673,
there were lots of forward

00:13:12.945 --> 00:13:17.210
contracts and lots of people
trading in these,

00:13:17.210 --> 00:13:22.415
so someone in Dojima thought,
why don't we set up a big

00:13:22.415 --> 00:13:28.199
market for these because people
have trouble knowing what the

00:13:28.199 --> 00:13:33.255
price is for a forward contract.
People would travel around from

00:13:33.255 --> 00:13:36.120
one warehouse to another and
they'd get a different price

00:13:36.120 --> 00:13:39.138
from one or the other;
they'd kind of wonder what the

00:13:39.138 --> 00:13:41.746
price is today,
so someone said well why don't

00:13:41.746 --> 00:13:44.759
we kind of create a market for
forward contracts.

00:13:44.759 --> 00:13:47.600
But, we don't call them forward
contracts;

00:13:47.600 --> 00:13:49.951
I don't know what they called
them in Japan,

00:13:49.951 --> 00:13:52.029
but I just want you to get the
idea.

00:13:52.029 --> 00:13:54.223
The idea is,
let's create a marketplace,

00:13:54.223 --> 00:13:57.542
a central marketplace so that
all these different--you don't

00:13:57.542 --> 00:14:00.917
have to go around to a hundred
different warehouses to try to

00:14:00.917 --> 00:14:03.694
find the best price;
you find out what the real

00:14:03.694 --> 00:14:07.363
price is.
What they did was they created

00:14:07.363 --> 00:14:13.374
an exchange in Dojima and the
exchange had a lot of modern

00:14:13.374 --> 00:14:17.580
features;
it had a trading floor.

00:14:17.580 --> 00:14:22.957
There was a designated area
where people who wanted to trade

00:14:22.957 --> 00:14:28.699
in rice futures would congregate
and all trades were supposed to

00:14:28.699 --> 00:14:31.685
be done there,
so it became a central

00:14:31.685 --> 00:14:34.628
marketplace.
So many people came to the

00:14:34.628 --> 00:14:39.584
exchange floor that it got very
noisy and traders can be very

00:14:39.584 --> 00:14:43.220
noisy people--shouting and
getting upset;

00:14:43.220 --> 00:14:47.598
trading rapidly back and forth.
So, they developed,

00:14:47.598 --> 00:14:51.301
in Dojima, a set of hand
signals so that it was so noisy

00:14:51.301 --> 00:14:55.070
and loud that you couldn't talk
sometimes and it was hard

00:14:55.070 --> 00:14:58.840
to--especially to communicate
something to someone on the

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:02.839
other side of the room.
So, they invented hand signals

00:15:02.839 --> 00:15:06.929
so the traders would be--I don't
know exactly what they were,

00:15:06.929 --> 00:15:08.867
but typically when the--if you
had something like this--you

00:15:08.867 --> 00:15:10.070
hold your hand with your palm
out,

00:15:10.070 --> 00:15:13.079
that means I want to sell and
if it's four fingers up,

00:15:13.079 --> 00:15:16.654
that means four contracts.
If you put it this way,

00:15:16.654 --> 00:15:20.179
it would be buying;
I want to buy four contracts.

00:15:20.179 --> 00:15:25.597
Those hand signals developed in
Osaka and they became a mainstay

00:15:25.597 --> 00:15:32.310
of futures markets after that.
Another thing they did in Japan

00:15:32.310 --> 00:15:39.720
to create the central market was
to standardize the rice.

00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:50.863
Now, this is very important;
if you go shopping around to

00:15:50.863 --> 00:15:54.189
different warehouses to try to
buy rice, you'll get some

00:15:54.189 --> 00:15:57.314
warehouse who says,
well I'm charging a higher

00:15:57.314 --> 00:16:01.179
price but my rice is better then
that other guy's rice.

00:16:01.179 --> 00:16:04.350
His has some worms in it
sometimes;

00:16:04.350 --> 00:16:09.090
don't trust that other guy,
or whatever it is.

00:16:09.090 --> 00:16:13.128
Rice isn't all the same;
there are different varieties

00:16:13.128 --> 00:16:15.870
and some of them taste better
than others.

00:16:15.870 --> 00:16:19.040
So, how would you ever know
what the price of rice is;

00:16:19.040 --> 00:16:23.203
it's just a mess.
What they did in Osaka is they

00:16:23.203 --> 00:16:29.289
made a standard form of rice for
delivery in their contract.

00:16:29.289 --> 00:16:34.036
That's important because
it--there are many kinds of

00:16:34.036 --> 00:16:39.807
rice, but they picked one that's
maybe the most common and then

00:16:39.807 --> 00:16:42.174
they said,
that's what all of our

00:16:42.174 --> 00:16:44.667
contracts are about;
so, you would be taking

00:16:44.667 --> 00:16:48.241
delivery of a standard rice.
Moreover, at the exchange,

00:16:48.241 --> 00:16:52.059
they had experts on rice who
could tell whether it was that

00:16:52.059 --> 00:16:55.570
contract.
It's not the best rice;

00:16:55.570 --> 00:16:59.174
it's the most common rice.
I visited the coffee,

00:16:59.174 --> 00:17:03.401
sugar and cocoa exchange in New
York once and jokingly I said,

00:17:03.401 --> 00:17:07.274
can I have a cup of coffee?
This is the coffee,

00:17:07.274 --> 00:17:11.289
sugar and cocoa exchange;
surely I can get a cup of

00:17:11.289 --> 00:17:13.118
coffee here.
Then the guy said,

00:17:13.118 --> 00:17:16.344
who was showing me around,
he said, well we could give you

00:17:16.344 --> 00:17:19.230
a cup of coffee but it's not
what we trade here.

00:17:19.230 --> 00:17:22.640
He says, you wouldn't like the
coffee we trade here;

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:25.829
it's not Starbucks;
it's the most standard.

00:17:25.829 --> 00:17:29.567
So, they set up a standard for
coffee at the coffee--maybe he

00:17:29.567 --> 00:17:32.187
was being too candid.
I don't know if they would say

00:17:32.187 --> 00:17:34.437
that officially.
They set up a standard for

00:17:34.437 --> 00:17:37.530
coffee at the coffee,
sugar, cocoa exchange and then

00:17:37.530 --> 00:17:40.502
no one would ever deliver better
coffee than that,

00:17:40.502 --> 00:17:43.400
right?
Well, I have to explain that.

00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:45.249
Everyone--well,
they wouldn't even be allowed

00:17:45.249 --> 00:17:47.960
to;
the whole idea is the contract

00:17:47.960 --> 00:17:51.115
has standards.
What actually happens--if you

00:17:51.115 --> 00:17:55.188
have a contract to deliver rice
or coffee or anything like that

00:17:55.188 --> 00:17:58.933
and there's some expert there
who's going to judge whether

00:17:58.933 --> 00:18:02.810
what you delivered was up to
quality standards and you are a

00:18:02.810 --> 00:18:07.113
smart businessperson,
you will deliver exactly the

00:18:07.113 --> 00:18:10.720
minimum quality to fulfill the
contract.

00:18:10.720 --> 00:18:14.591
It'll never be below the
minimum quality because no one

00:18:14.591 --> 00:18:18.430
can deliver it;
the testers will not allow that.

00:18:18.430 --> 00:18:21.993
And it can't be above the
minimum standard because you'd

00:18:21.993 --> 00:18:24.309
never do that;
you'd be stupid to do that.

00:18:24.309 --> 00:18:27.690
So, you always--it always
becomes the standard variety.

00:18:27.690 --> 00:18:33.958
What they did at the futures
market is they then not only had

00:18:33.958 --> 00:18:39.392
standardized the rice,
but they standardized delivery

00:18:39.392 --> 00:18:42.840
dates and delivery locations.

00:18:46.470 --> 00:18:50.859
What would you trade in these
futures markets?

00:18:50.859 --> 00:18:55.149
You would be trading--you'd
either be buying or selling rice

00:18:55.149 --> 00:18:59.148
for future delivery on a
standardized delivery date at a

00:18:59.148 --> 00:19:03.656
standardized location--probably
one of the warehouses that they

00:19:03.656 --> 00:19:08.114
designate.
That might not be the rice you

00:19:08.114 --> 00:19:14.374
want or the date you want and
yet, somehow the market gets

00:19:14.374 --> 00:19:19.010
going and gets very big.
This is the reason:

00:19:19.010 --> 00:19:23.318
what a futures market does
that's different from a

00:19:23.318 --> 00:19:28.505
warehouse market is it sets up a
standard price and a liquid

00:19:28.505 --> 00:19:32.408
market.
So, people end up using the

00:19:32.408 --> 00:19:38.843
futures market to lock in the
price or to hedge price risk and

00:19:38.843 --> 00:19:45.489
they know that the price in the
futures market is the meaningful

00:19:45.489 --> 00:19:50.059
price.
You hear all kinds of prices of

00:19:50.059 --> 00:19:52.609
rice;
there will be rumors here and

00:19:52.609 --> 00:19:56.258
there that someone will say,
I saw rice sell for such and

00:19:56.258 --> 00:19:58.799
such--so many Yen or whatever it
is.

00:19:58.799 --> 00:20:00.859
Don't believe any of that
nonsense.

00:20:00.859 --> 00:20:03.972
Who knows what was sold or what
terms there were or what

00:20:03.972 --> 00:20:07.456
exigencies there were.
Only look at the futures market

00:20:07.456 --> 00:20:11.230
because the futures market is
absolutely standardized.

00:20:11.230 --> 00:20:13.903
You know the terms of delivery,
the location,

00:20:13.903 --> 00:20:17.720
and everything else.
What ended up happening is that

00:20:17.720 --> 00:20:22.599
everyone wanted to trade in the
futures market and it became a

00:20:22.599 --> 00:20:27.160
huge market and then everyone
started watching the futures

00:20:27.160 --> 00:20:34.240
price.
That's what we now have;

00:20:34.240 --> 00:20:37.860
that's what is in a futures-- I
wanted to tell you one other

00:20:37.860 --> 00:20:41.296
curious thing about the--well,
two other things about the

00:20:41.296 --> 00:20:44.864
Osaka market.
They had trading hours,

00:20:44.864 --> 00:20:47.768
just as do today.
In other words,

00:20:47.768 --> 00:20:51.419
only certain hours of the day
the floor was open and then it

00:20:51.419 --> 00:20:54.649
was shut off.
People would get very excited

00:20:54.649 --> 00:20:58.475
and trade very actively;
you have to somehow let people

00:20:58.475 --> 00:21:02.330
know that the trading time is
over and all trades have to stop

00:21:02.330 --> 00:21:05.337
at the end of the day.
So, they had a burning fuse,

00:21:05.337 --> 00:21:08.446
which they would light in the
middle of the trading floor just

00:21:08.446 --> 00:21:11.555
a few minutes before the end of
the day and you could see this

00:21:11.555 --> 00:21:14.562
flame and that meant you better
finish your trades right now

00:21:14.562 --> 00:21:17.750
because when the flame goes out,
it's over.

00:21:17.750 --> 00:21:22.825
We don't have fuses anymore;
we have clocks and a bell that

00:21:22.825 --> 00:21:25.809
announces the beginning and end
at an exchange.

00:21:25.809 --> 00:21:29.211
There's one other thing they
had, which I think is kind of

00:21:29.211 --> 00:21:32.856
curious that hasn't been copied.
They had people called

00:21:32.856 --> 00:21:37.265
watermen, who after the fuse
went out they carried buckets of

00:21:37.265 --> 00:21:41.473
water onto the exchange.
If anybody was still trading,

00:21:41.473 --> 00:21:45.781
they splashed them with water.
That was to douse the--the fuse

00:21:45.781 --> 00:21:47.910
is out;
everything is doused for today.

00:21:47.910 --> 00:21:51.769
We don't do that in modern
futures exchanges.

00:21:51.769 --> 00:21:53.809
Of course, it's all electronic
now;

00:21:53.809 --> 00:21:56.177
there's no--well,
it's getting increasingly

00:21:56.177 --> 00:21:59.607
electronic.
The CME and the CBOT still have

00:21:59.607 --> 00:22:05.002
trading floors like Dojima's and
they're still using these hand

00:22:05.002 --> 00:22:10.010
signals,
but it's getting lonely there

00:22:10.010 --> 00:22:18.529
because everything is moving
away to the electronic markets.

00:22:18.529 --> 00:22:22.569
You'll still see on CNBC,
Bob Pisani will be standing at

00:22:22.569 --> 00:22:27.196
the T-bond trading pit and he'll
give his little--they focus the

00:22:27.196 --> 00:22:31.603
camera right on where all the
people are at and they're still

00:22:31.603 --> 00:22:36.230
out there jostling each other
and shouting at each other.

00:22:36.230 --> 00:22:39.757
So, it's still going on,
but it's increasingly becoming

00:22:39.757 --> 00:22:44.351
an electronic market.
I guess the most important

00:22:44.351 --> 00:22:50.654
thing to realize about futures
markets is that they're

00:22:50.654 --> 00:22:57.313
different from forward markets
in that it--with a futures

00:22:57.313 --> 00:23:00.468
market,
when you buy and sell a

00:23:00.468 --> 00:23:04.904
contract you are buying and
selling with the exchange or the

00:23:04.904 --> 00:23:10.160
clearing house of the exchange.
You do not know the counter

00:23:10.160 --> 00:23:12.351
party;
you do not know who's on the

00:23:12.351 --> 00:23:15.963
other side.
With a forward market,

00:23:15.963 --> 00:23:21.910
you know very well who's on the
other side;

00:23:21.910 --> 00:23:25.182
you're going to a warehouse and
there's this warehouse who's

00:23:25.182 --> 00:23:28.072
going to take your grain.
In the warehouse,

00:23:28.072 --> 00:23:33.069
you better trust the other side
because suppose the other side

00:23:33.069 --> 00:23:36.001
doesn't work.
Suppose you have your--you've

00:23:36.001 --> 00:23:39.412
loaded up all your rice and you
come to the warehouse and then

00:23:39.412 --> 00:23:41.537
the guy says,
I don't want to honor the

00:23:41.537 --> 00:23:42.861
contract.
I signed it,

00:23:42.861 --> 00:23:44.440
but I'm just not going to take
it;

00:23:44.440 --> 00:23:46.809
I'm going to lower the price on
you.

00:23:46.809 --> 00:23:50.140
Then you have to sue this guy
and it's a big mess.

00:23:50.140 --> 00:23:53.966
The problem with forward
contracts is that they're not

00:23:53.966 --> 00:23:56.200
standardized;
you're not dealing with a

00:23:56.200 --> 00:23:58.242
reputable exchange.
With an exchange,

00:23:58.242 --> 00:24:00.619
there is of course a counter
party.

00:24:00.619 --> 00:24:03.885
If you're selling rice and
someone else is buying it,

00:24:03.885 --> 00:24:07.779
there's an intermediary between
you and that's the exchange.

00:24:07.779 --> 00:24:10.186
Since the exchange will honor
any contract,

00:24:10.186 --> 00:24:12.880
you don't have to worry about
the other side.

00:24:12.880 --> 00:24:19.593
That's another reason why
futures prices are so much more

00:24:19.593 --> 00:24:26.307
meaningful than spot or forward
prices because there's no

00:24:26.307 --> 00:24:34.220
counter-party risk unless you
worry about the exchange itself.

00:24:34.220 --> 00:24:36.630
Since the futures exchanges in
the U.S.

00:24:36.630 --> 00:24:39.226
have been here since the
nineteenth century and they've

00:24:39.226 --> 00:24:42.028
never lost a contract,
people assume as a first

00:24:42.028 --> 00:24:44.980
approximation,
that there's no counter-party

00:24:44.980 --> 00:24:49.045
risk.
I still haven't maybe fully

00:24:49.045 --> 00:24:53.377
explained futures.
Let me--before we go on,

00:24:53.377 --> 00:24:57.712
I want to talk a little bit
about forwards because now we

00:24:57.712 --> 00:25:01.620
have a slide up here.
We do have forward contracts

00:25:01.620 --> 00:25:04.769
and they still play an important
function.

00:25:04.769 --> 00:25:09.870
The reason is that futures
markets, by their very nature,

00:25:09.870 --> 00:25:15.608
are standardized markets.
Or you might say they're retail

00:25:15.608 --> 00:25:17.458
markets.
They have a huge number of

00:25:17.458 --> 00:25:19.359
people trading in them,
but it's all a standard thing.

00:25:19.359 --> 00:25:24.721
Forward markets are between
persons and so they can be--the

00:25:24.721 --> 00:25:28.049
contract can be anything you
want.

00:25:28.049 --> 00:25:33.929
So, forward contracts are very
important but they tend to be

00:25:33.929 --> 00:25:39.510
less--I tend to observe them
less because they don't have

00:25:39.510 --> 00:25:43.880
this newsworthy character.
Everyone's talking about

00:25:43.880 --> 00:25:46.814
futures prices because everyone
knows that is a very

00:25:46.814 --> 00:25:48.424
well-defined,
central market,

00:25:48.424 --> 00:25:53.057
liquid price.
The forward contracts are not

00:25:53.057 --> 00:25:55.460
liquid;
you can't get out of it.

00:25:55.460 --> 00:26:00.117
So if you, as a rice merchant,
sold your rice--as a rice

00:26:00.117 --> 00:26:04.944
farmer--you sold your rice
forward to a warehouse and then

00:26:04.944 --> 00:26:09.940
you change your mind--you want
to get out--you can't because

00:26:09.940 --> 00:26:13.291
unless the other guy says,
I'll let you out,

00:26:13.291 --> 00:26:14.650
because you've just got a
contract.

00:26:14.650 --> 00:26:18.755
The futures has this active
trading in and out,

00:26:18.755 --> 00:26:21.789
so the prices seem to mean
more.

00:26:21.789 --> 00:26:24.170
Let's talk about forward
markets.

00:26:24.170 --> 00:26:26.130
There are forward markets for a
lot of things.

00:26:26.130 --> 00:26:29.804
One very important forward
market is the foreign exchange

00:26:29.804 --> 00:26:32.768
forward market.
This happens a lot because

00:26:32.768 --> 00:26:36.892
there are tons of businesses
that have--they sell things in

00:26:36.892 --> 00:26:41.299
countries around the world and
they get foreign currencies.

00:26:41.299 --> 00:26:45.273
If you sell some--you're a
manufacturer and you sell

00:26:45.273 --> 00:26:49.091
something in Japan,
then they're paying you in yen

00:26:49.091 --> 00:26:52.910
and they might be paying you in
three months.

00:26:52.910 --> 00:26:56.528
So, you worry about the
exchange rate between dollars

00:26:56.528 --> 00:26:59.589
and yen, so you want to get it
in dollars.

00:26:59.589 --> 00:27:03.780
You might want to find a
counter party who will exchange

00:27:03.780 --> 00:27:08.579
your yen for dollars in three
months or whatever the term is;

00:27:08.579 --> 00:27:11.916
that's called a forward
contract for exchange of

00:27:11.916 --> 00:27:14.619
currencies.
Very simple.

00:27:14.619 --> 00:27:19.418
I'm getting--I'm selling cars
in Japan--that sounds--that does

00:27:19.418 --> 00:27:22.150
happen--U.S.
cars sold in Japan.

00:27:22.150 --> 00:27:25.596
So, I'm going to get--I know
I'm going to get this yen in

00:27:25.596 --> 00:27:28.490
three months.
I just signed a contract with

00:27:28.490 --> 00:27:32.430
somebody to exchange dollars--we
fixed the exchange rate;

00:27:32.430 --> 00:27:34.269
that's called the forward
exchange rate.

00:27:34.269 --> 00:27:37.849
It's not necessarily the same
as today's exchange rate;

00:27:37.849 --> 00:27:40.410
in fact, it would generally be
systematically different.

00:27:40.410 --> 00:27:44.517
So, we have this,
what's called forward interest

00:27:44.517 --> 00:27:47.656
parity relation.
The forward--this is an

00:27:47.656 --> 00:27:51.538
arbitrage relationship that
holds very well in the forward

00:27:51.538 --> 00:27:55.831
market for foreign exchange.
The forward exchange

00:27:55.831 --> 00:28:00.193
rate--that's yen per dollar,
in the case,

00:28:00.193 --> 00:28:05.973
if we're talking about Japan
and U.S.--equals the spot

00:28:05.973 --> 00:28:12.516
exchange rate that's in yen per
dollar times one plus the yen

00:28:12.516 --> 00:28:18.950
interest rate--that's for three
months if it's a three-month

00:28:18.950 --> 00:28:24.839
horizon--times one plus dollar
interest rate.

00:28:24.839 --> 00:28:28.599
And that relation holds very
well.

00:28:28.599 --> 00:28:33.678
If it didn't hold,
I could make money quickly

00:28:33.678 --> 00:28:38.410
without risk and that shouldn't
happen.

00:28:38.410 --> 00:28:42.404
Think of it this way,
the interest rate in Japan is

00:28:42.404 --> 00:28:46.079
different from the interest rate
in the U.S.

00:28:46.079 --> 00:28:50.660
Government bonds issued in
Japan are perfectly safe.

00:28:50.660 --> 00:28:54.155
Well, I mean you could say of
course the Japanese government

00:28:54.155 --> 00:28:56.880
could default,
but it's not going to happen.

00:28:56.880 --> 00:29:00.846
To a first approximation,
it's not going to--we'll call

00:29:00.846 --> 00:29:04.539
it a zero probability.
Same thing with the U.S.

00:29:04.539 --> 00:29:08.029
How can two different countries
have different interest rates?

00:29:08.029 --> 00:29:10.224
You would think,
well wouldn't an investor

00:29:10.224 --> 00:29:13.490
always invest in the country
with the higher interest rate?

00:29:13.490 --> 00:29:16.605
Why not if it's riskless?
Well, there is risk and that's

00:29:16.605 --> 00:29:19.710
exchange rate risk.
You can get rid of the risk by

00:29:19.710 --> 00:29:22.319
taking a forward contract.
You could say,

00:29:22.319 --> 00:29:25.556
if you're living in Japan,
I note that interest rates are

00:29:25.556 --> 00:29:28.884
higher in the U.S.
than Japan, so I'm not going to

00:29:28.884 --> 00:29:31.750
go--I'm not going to invest in
yen bonds;

00:29:31.750 --> 00:29:33.410
I'm going to invest in U.S.
bonds.

00:29:33.410 --> 00:29:37.956
Then, I'm going to cover myself
by making a forward contract to

00:29:37.956 --> 00:29:42.266
get the money back in yen.
Well, that's a very clear thing

00:29:42.266 --> 00:29:46.489
to do, but the problem is you
can't make any money doing it

00:29:46.489 --> 00:29:49.619
because this holds because of
arbitrage.

00:29:49.619 --> 00:29:52.908
There are so many people who've
noticed that--that interest

00:29:52.908 --> 00:29:55.980
rates are higher in the U.S.
than Japan;

00:29:55.980 --> 00:29:57.410
they're both riskless interest
rates.

00:29:57.410 --> 00:30:01.600
It can't be right that there's
this profit opportunity that's

00:30:01.600 --> 00:30:05.232
riskless, so the forward
exchange rate satisfies this

00:30:05.232 --> 00:30:08.456
relationship.
The forward rate equals the

00:30:08.456 --> 00:30:11.849
spot rate times the relative
interest rates.

00:30:11.849 --> 00:30:15.738
This is over the horizon
between now--this is not the

00:30:15.738 --> 00:30:19.477
annual interest rate,
unless it's an annual forward

00:30:19.477 --> 00:30:22.380
contract.
If it's a three-month forward

00:30:22.380 --> 00:30:26.174
contract this would be the
interest earned in three months

00:30:26.174 --> 00:30:30.101
in yen and this would be the
interest earned in dollars over

00:30:30.101 --> 00:30:33.151
three months.
That's one kind of forward rate

00:30:33.151 --> 00:30:35.720
agreement and this market works
very well.

00:30:35.720 --> 00:30:37.878
It satisfies this
relation--we've explained--we

00:30:37.878 --> 00:30:40.556
know this market;
it just satisfies the forward

00:30:40.556 --> 00:30:49.773
interest parity condition.
Another forward market is the

00:30:49.773 --> 00:30:59.410
market for different interest
rates.

00:30:59.410 --> 00:31:07.465
We can have a forward loan.
We can say, I want to make a

00:31:07.465 --> 00:31:10.319
loan at a future date of a
certain maturity;

00:31:10.319 --> 00:31:15.729
let's tie in the interest rate
now, so R is the contract

00:31:15.729 --> 00:31:18.424
rate.
Suppose you want to either

00:31:18.424 --> 00:31:21.309
borrow or lend money in the
future;

00:31:21.309 --> 00:31:24.314
we talked about forward rates
implicit in the term structure

00:31:24.314 --> 00:31:27.268
earlier and you could try to
achieve those forward rates as

00:31:27.268 --> 00:31:30.068
we talked about earlier by
buying and selling government

00:31:30.068 --> 00:31:31.903
bonds,
but this is another way to do

00:31:31.903 --> 00:31:35.930
it, which may be simpler.
It doesn't involve shorting

00:31:35.930 --> 00:31:38.089
bonds;
you can just make a contract.

00:31:38.089 --> 00:31:42.746
There's a contract rate in the
forward contract and the

00:31:42.746 --> 00:31:47.402
contract says--the contract
specifies the contract rate

00:31:47.402 --> 00:31:52.490
R and the number of days
in the contract period;

00:31:52.490 --> 00:31:56.507
that's how many days hence this
contract will be delivered--will

00:31:56.507 --> 00:31:59.235
be executed.
You can make any forward rate

00:31:59.235 --> 00:32:02.210
contract you want,
but this is the most standard

00:32:02.210 --> 00:32:04.492
contract;
yet, it's between counter

00:32:04.492 --> 00:32:07.049
parties, so you can do whatever
you want.

00:32:07.049 --> 00:32:10.121
But, if you talk with a broker
and you got a standard contract

00:32:10.121 --> 00:32:12.722
you'd probably get this.
Now, the purpose of this

00:32:12.722 --> 00:32:14.930
contract is to lock in an
interest rate.

00:32:14.930 --> 00:32:18.053
It's a risk management
contract, so you don't actually

00:32:18.053 --> 00:32:21.177
want to borrow and lend from
this other person--you'll

00:32:21.177 --> 00:32:24.949
arrange that separately--but you
want to protect yourself so that

00:32:24.949 --> 00:32:28.839
you know today what interest
rate you can get in the future.

00:32:28.839 --> 00:32:37.020
What they do is they define
some measure of actual interest

00:32:37.020 --> 00:32:45.764
rate and it could be something
like LIBOR, the London Interbank

00:32:45.764 --> 00:32:49.680
Offer Rate;
it's just an interest rate

00:32:49.680 --> 00:32:52.380
that's defined by an agency in
London.

00:32:52.380 --> 00:32:54.160
They have a website and you can
read it.

00:32:54.160 --> 00:32:57.119
It's a well-known,
well-defined interest rate.

00:32:57.119 --> 00:33:00.831
So, you could say,
three-month LIBOR is the

00:33:00.831 --> 00:33:04.807
interest rate,
90 days in the future--D

00:33:04.807 --> 00:33:08.824
would be 90 and so,
what the contract specifies--it

00:33:08.824 --> 00:33:11.640
also specifies a contract
amount, A,

00:33:11.640 --> 00:33:16.816
and B is actually
usually 360, but sometimes

00:33:16.816 --> 00:33:20.410
they'll say 365.
You can write whatever you want

00:33:20.410 --> 00:33:23.200
in these contracts,
but this is standard--typically

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:26.185
360 days.
So, all it specified--what the

00:33:26.185 --> 00:33:29.660
contract says--there are two
counterparties;

00:33:29.660 --> 00:33:33.539
there's the long and the short;
somebody is receiving interest

00:33:33.539 --> 00:33:37.714
and someone is paying interest.
The settlement is this amount,

00:33:37.714 --> 00:33:42.145
from one side to the other.
This formula actually--it

00:33:42.145 --> 00:33:46.536
doesn't appear in Fabozzi in
exactly this notation,

00:33:46.536 --> 00:33:50.839
but this is in the chapter on
futures markets.

00:33:50.839 --> 00:33:53.753
This equation,
although it's written a little

00:33:53.753 --> 00:33:57.593
differently, it's the same
equation that appears in Fabozzi

00:33:57.593 --> 00:34:00.109
in the chapter on futures
markets.

00:34:00.109 --> 00:34:03.954
What you do,
the standard forward contract

00:34:03.954 --> 00:34:09.675
says, one counter party pays the
other this amount and that is

00:34:09.675 --> 00:34:15.489
equal to the actual interest
rate minus the contract rate,

00:34:15.489 --> 00:34:21.184
times the number of days,
times the contract amount,

00:34:21.184 --> 00:34:27.247
divided by B, times 100.
This 100 is here because

00:34:27.247 --> 00:34:32.201
L and R are
assumed to be measured in

00:34:32.201 --> 00:34:37.353
hundreds, like percent--3% is
really .03 x L x

00:34:37.353 --> 00:34:41.397
D.
This equation might be easier

00:34:41.397 --> 00:34:47.169
if you divide both numerator and
denominator by 100 then you can

00:34:47.169 --> 00:34:52.849
see that all that 100 is doing
is correcting the interest rates

00:34:52.849 --> 00:34:58.542
from percent to--from 3% to .03.
All it's doing--all this

00:34:58.542 --> 00:35:04.009
contract is is an amount--a
promise--to pay the difference

00:35:04.009 --> 00:35:09.380
between the contract and the
actual interest rate on that

00:35:09.380 --> 00:35:12.292
date.
That effectively allows you,

00:35:12.292 --> 00:35:16.336
if you want to borrow at that
rate, to lock in the interest

00:35:16.336 --> 00:35:20.310
rate today because I will get an
amount of money from this

00:35:20.310 --> 00:35:24.563
contract that will offset any
changes in interest rates in the

00:35:24.563 --> 00:35:28.437
future.
That's another example of a

00:35:28.437 --> 00:35:32.719
contract.
