00:40:46.739 --> 00:40:52.086
Now, if you drive through the
country and turn on the radio,

00:40:52.086 --> 00:40:56.889
you will hear at regular
intervals--the announcer will

00:40:56.889 --> 00:41:02.764
tell you what corn is doing.
They say, corn at the latest

00:41:02.764 --> 00:41:09.320
trading is up to $2.18 a bushel.
What price is that guy quoting?

00:41:09.320 --> 00:41:12.769
It's always going to be the
futures price.

00:41:12.769 --> 00:41:15.141
You might say,
well that's two months in the

00:41:15.141 --> 00:41:17.236
future--March,
April, May--why are they

00:41:17.236 --> 00:41:20.009
talking about May?
Because this is March,

00:41:20.009 --> 00:41:24.263
why doesn't the announcer tells
us that at some warehouse the

00:41:24.263 --> 00:41:26.888
price today was?
The reason is that,

00:41:26.888 --> 00:41:30.052
as I was saying,
