00:41:33.350 --> 00:41:35.100
so this is the price.

00:41:41.840 --> 00:41:48.623
The other thing that I want to
emphasize is that these markets

00:41:48.623 --> 00:41:54.739
are used to manage risks of
holding or raising grain.

00:41:54.739 --> 00:41:58.367
Most of the time,
people who are trading in this

00:41:58.367 --> 00:42:01.300
market do not complete the
contract.

00:42:01.300 --> 00:42:04.660
In other words,
if I--let's say I'm a farmer

00:42:04.660 --> 00:42:09.036
raising corn and I'm worried
that the price of corn might

00:42:09.036 --> 00:42:12.710
fall while I'm raising it and I
lose money.

00:42:12.710 --> 00:42:17.939
If the world market for corn
drops, then I might not be able

00:42:17.939 --> 00:42:23.699
to cover my expenses this year
and so I could be at great risk.

00:42:23.699 --> 00:42:28.253
So, I can sell in the futures
market, but I probably won't

00:42:28.253 --> 00:42:31.920
deliver to the futures market.
Why not?

00:42:31.920 --> 00:42:36.411
Because the delivery point is
in Chicago and I'm a farmer in

00:42:36.411 --> 00:42:40.446
Iowa and I don't know how to
deliver it all the way to

00:42:40.446 --> 00:42:43.599
Chicago.
I'd have to rent trucks and

00:42:43.599 --> 00:42:47.239
drive to Chicago with my corn;
I'm not going to do that.

00:42:47.239 --> 00:42:50.500
I'm always just delivering to
the local grain elevator.

00:42:50.500 --> 00:42:52.679
In fact, I don't have to--I
don't need any trucks;

00:42:52.679 --> 00:42:56.885
the guy will pick it up from my
farm, so that's what I want to

00:42:56.885 --> 00:42:59.734
do.
What I do typically is I sell

00:42:59.734 --> 00:43:02.844
in the futures market,
I as a farmer,

00:43:02.844 --> 00:43:06.989
and then one day before the
contract expires,

00:43:06.989 --> 00:43:10.382
instead of delivering,
I will buy it back and cancel

00:43:10.382 --> 00:43:13.827
out my contract.
So, all I've done is a purely

00:43:13.827 --> 00:43:17.250
financial trade in the future.
Do you see the difference?

00:43:17.250 --> 00:43:20.951
I don't actually want to
deliver because it's too much

00:43:20.951 --> 00:43:24.374
trouble to deliver,
so you get farmers trading all

00:43:24.374 --> 00:43:28.425
over the country and all over
the world in this market as a

00:43:28.425 --> 00:43:33.163
way of hedging their corn.
Very few of them will ever

00:43:33.163 --> 00:43:36.770
deliver.
The only reason why delivery is

00:43:36.770 --> 00:43:42.162
kept open as an option is that
is what determines the price in

00:43:42.162 --> 00:43:45.904
the market.
Ultimately, the only people who

00:43:45.904 --> 00:43:50.427
deliver are professional
arbitragers, who on the last day

00:43:50.427 --> 00:43:53.820
or right when the contract is
expiring,

00:43:53.820 --> 00:43:56.079
they look at the futures price
and they say,

00:43:56.079 --> 00:43:58.707
maybe I can deliver it,
maybe I can buy it for less

00:43:58.707 --> 00:44:01.230
than that and deliver and I'll
really do it.

00:44:01.230 --> 00:44:05.181
Those are the only people;
so, if they can buy for less

00:44:05.181 --> 00:44:07.679
than that and deliver,
they'll do it.

00:44:07.679 --> 00:44:12.058
They compete with each other
and that brings the futures

00:44:12.058 --> 00:44:15.719
price and the spot price in line
at the end.

00:44:15.719 --> 00:44:19.013
Alternatively,
if the spot price is above the

00:44:19.013 --> 00:44:22.905
futures price at the end,
then these arbitragers will

00:44:22.905 --> 00:44:27.137
say, hey I'll take delivery.
I'll go there and take delivery

00:44:27.137 --> 00:44:30.219
on a contract and then I'll sell
it and make money.

00:44:30.219 --> 00:44:35.217
It's because of the arbitragers
that the cash price and the spot

00:44:35.217 --> 00:44:40.791
price line up at the end;
it's not through any law

00:44:40.791 --> 00:44:44.469
requirement.
You see what people are doing?

00:44:44.469 --> 00:44:47.530
They're using the futures
market as a purely financial

00:44:47.530 --> 00:44:50.704
market.
Most people rely on the

00:44:50.704 --> 00:44:57.284
arbitragers to enforce the
futures price converging on the

00:44:57.284 --> 00:45:01.563
spot price at the end.
Most people are not even

00:45:01.563 --> 00:45:03.769
raising the right kind of corn
maybe;

00:45:03.769 --> 00:45:06.389
I don't know how--a lot of them
certainly aren't.

00:45:06.389 --> 00:45:07.650
There are all different kinds
of corn.

00:45:07.650 --> 00:45:12.349
If you are raising one kind of
corn and are hedging your risks

00:45:12.349 --> 00:45:17.050
with a different kind of corn,
that's called cross-hedging.

00:45:17.050 --> 00:45:26.766
That means across products;
I'm going from one product to

00:45:26.766 --> 00:45:29.180
another.
So, I could be raising some of

00:45:29.180 --> 00:45:32.591
this beautiful Indian corn
that--remember it turns all

00:45:32.591 --> 00:45:36.324
these different colors and
people hang it on their doors at

00:45:36.324 --> 00:45:40.250
Halloween--that's not suitable
for delivery at the CBOT.

00:45:40.250 --> 00:45:43.951
If I'm raising that,
there's no market--it's no

00:45:43.951 --> 00:45:47.010
future--it's no big market for
that,

00:45:47.010 --> 00:45:49.305
but it probably correlates with
regular corn,

00:45:49.305 --> 00:45:52.252
so I could cross-hedge.
If I'm raising Indian corn and

00:45:52.252 --> 00:45:55.153
I'm worried about the price,
I can sell in the futures

00:45:55.153 --> 00:45:57.889
market in Chicago and buy it
back the next day.

