going, we're driving some people
to starvation.

00:50:36.920 --> 00:50:40.854
On the other hand,
I don't mean to minimize that,

00:50:40.854 --> 00:50:45.772
I thought it was interesting to
look at the whole run of corn

00:50:45.772 --> 00:50:50.227
prices back to 1929;
they have come down a great

00:50:50.227 --> 00:50:52.672
deal.
It's quite curious,

00:50:52.672 --> 00:50:58.466
if you correct for inflation;
it was like $15 a bushel in

00:50:58.466 --> 00:50:59.943
1950.
On top of that,

00:50:59.943 --> 00:51:03.471
our incomes have risen and so I
think this says something about

00:51:03.471 --> 00:51:06.715
why futures--agricultural
futures--are not as prominent as

00:51:06.715 --> 00:51:09.836
they used to be.
It used to be that food was

00:51:09.836 --> 00:51:14.260
really a lot more expensive and
a bigger share of our income.

00:51:14.260 --> 00:51:17.579
We live in a very plenteous
time;

00:51:17.579 --> 00:51:19.730
this is very unusual by
historical standards.

00:51:19.730 --> 00:51:22.820
Right now, you just eat
whatever you want;

00:51:22.820 --> 00:51:24.740
you don't even look at the
price;

00:51:24.740 --> 00:51:27.030
it's all so cheap.
Maybe you do;

00:51:27.030 --> 00:51:30.279
maybe you don't eat caviar
because of price,

00:51:30.279 --> 00:51:34.510
but we're just in a time of
plenty with the real price of

00:51:34.510 --> 00:51:37.635
food so low.
It's not normal times,

00:51:37.635 --> 00:51:41.467
historically,
so our agricultural futures are

00:51:41.467 --> 00:51:46.860
somewhat downplayed.
I wanted to give an example of

00:51:46.860 --> 00:51:52.961
wheat futures because this
is--we have a reading on the

00:51:52.961 --> 00:51:57.030
reading list by Holbrook
Working.

00:51:57.030 --> 00:52:01.702
Holbrook Working was the great
theorist of futures markets and

00:52:01.702 --> 00:52:05.992
it's actually--the reading comes
from the 1950s and he is

00:52:05.992 --> 00:52:10.300
explaining futures market.
I like this article because it

00:52:10.300 --> 00:52:14.054
sets it forth very well and
nothing has changed since the

00:52:14.054 --> 00:52:17.539
1950s except that the markets
are electronic now.

00:52:17.539 --> 00:52:22.332
I wanted to focus in on one
futures market and this is the

00:52:22.332 --> 00:52:26.380
market for wheat.
These are the standards for

00:52:26.380 --> 00:52:30.010
delivery at the Chicago Board of
Trade.

00:52:30.010 --> 00:52:32.490
I got this off their website
and this current;

00:52:32.490 --> 00:52:36.779
this is today.
If you--one contract is 5,000

00:52:36.779 --> 00:52:40.443
bushels.
They will accept a number of

00:52:40.443 --> 00:52:45.908
different kinds of wheat that
meet their--there must be some

00:52:45.908 --> 00:52:51.280
standards for quality--no bugs
in it and whatever else--but

00:52:51.280 --> 00:52:56.745
they'll accept number two soft
red winter or number two hard

00:52:56.745 --> 00:53:02.210
red winter or--I just copied
this from the--it says,

00:53:02.210 --> 00:53:06.474
no dark northern spring.
It must be number something,

00:53:06.474 --> 00:53:09.298
what happened?
I must have lost the--number

00:53:09.298 --> 00:53:12.440
two, northern spring.
All those are at par.

00:53:12.440 --> 00:53:17.440
However, you can also deliver
number one soft red winter.

00:53:17.440 --> 00:53:20.977
That's different because this
is number two soft red

00:53:20.977 --> 00:53:24.792
winter--or number one hard red
winter or number one dark

00:53:24.792 --> 00:53:28.329
northern spring and number one
northern spring;

00:53:28.329 --> 00:53:31.409
you get $.03 a bushel over the
contract price.

00:53:31.409 --> 00:53:37.548
What they're trying to do is
recognize that there are so many

00:53:37.548 --> 00:53:43.278
different kinds of wheat and so
I thought we would remind

00:53:43.278 --> 00:53:49.720
ourselves of what they are.
One hard--soft wheat is used

00:53:49.720 --> 00:53:55.909
for making biscuits and
breakfast cereals and cakes;

00:53:55.909 --> 00:53:59.230
hard wheat is used for making
bread.

00:53:59.230 --> 00:54:02.634
If you do baking,
you should not just always use

00:54:02.634 --> 00:54:05.965
all-purpose flour,
you should get the different

00:54:05.965 --> 00:54:08.789
varieties.
That's what is being mentioned

00:54:08.789 --> 00:54:13.807
here--these different varieties.
I wanted to--let me see,

00:54:13.807 --> 00:54:20.239
I wanted to talk about the
Holbrook Working paper.

00:54:20.239 --> 00:54:30.417
Holbrook Working talks about
winter--is anyone here who is a

00:54:30.417 --> 00:54:35.039
farmer?
Did anyone grow up on a farm?

00:54:35.039 --> 00:54:37.900
Can anyone tell the story of
winter wheat?

00:54:37.900 --> 00:54:41.747
Nobody?
We're not very down-to-earth

00:54:41.747 --> 00:54:46.820
people here, are we?
There are two plantings;

00:54:46.820 --> 00:54:48.550
there's winter wheat and spring
wheat.

00:54:48.550 --> 00:54:52.613
Winter wheat--you plant it in
the winter and you harvest it in

00:54:52.613 --> 00:54:55.060
the spring.
It stays in the ground all

00:54:55.060 --> 00:54:58.464
winter and it comes up first
thing in the--it's coming up

00:54:58.464 --> 00:55:00.695
now.
You harvest winter wheat in

00:55:00.695 --> 00:55:03.570
May, so we're almost close to
the harvest.

00:55:03.570 --> 00:55:07.347
Did you know that?
There are amber waves of grain

00:55:07.347 --> 00:55:12.593
blowing in the wind out there in
the wheat belt right now and it

00:55:12.593 --> 00:55:17.090
will soon be harvested in
another month and a half.

00:55:17.090 --> 00:55:20.572
Spring wheat--you plant it in
the spring and you harvest it in

00:55:20.572 --> 00:55:22.650
the fall.
But they're allowing now

00:55:22.650 --> 00:55:26.208
delivery of either one.
When Holbrook Working wrote the

00:55:26.208 --> 00:55:30.084
paper, there was a separate
contract for hard winter wheat

00:55:30.084 --> 00:55:34.301
and so I think that there's some
consolidation of these markets

00:55:34.301 --> 00:55:38.110
as agricultural futures is
becoming less important.

00:55:38.110 --> 00:55:42.311
That's why we just have--this
is the only CBOT wheat market

00:55:42.311 --> 00:55:46.647
that's listed now.
You understand what the

00:55:46.647 --> 00:55:49.910
contract is?
The contract is to deliver one

00:55:49.910 --> 00:55:53.224
of these varieties and there's a
separate contract for each of

00:55:53.224 --> 00:56:00.949
these dates.
What is the pricing?

00:56:00.949 --> 00:56:03.659
This is the thing--what is the
futures price?

00:56:03.659 --> 00:56:09.539
Now there's--this is what I'm
going to try to conclude on.

00:56:09.539 --> 00:56:13.969
It depends on whether wheat is
in storage or not.

00:56:13.969 --> 00:56:18.019
Normally, wheat is in storage
because we only harvest a

00:56:18.019 --> 00:56:22.445
particular variety once a year
and we have to consume it all

00:56:22.445 --> 00:56:25.330
year.
So, after the harvest the

00:56:25.330 --> 00:56:30.460
warehouses get full and then
they're brimming with wheat.

00:56:30.460 --> 00:56:34.983
Then, as the year goes down,
the warehouses deplete their

00:56:34.983 --> 00:56:39.829
contents of wheat and it hits
zero right when the new harvest

00:56:39.829 --> 00:56:43.009
comes in.
Then, it all gets put back into

00:56:43.009 --> 00:56:45.510
the warehouse.
This is a physical necessity.

00:56:45.510 --> 00:56:52.126
When there is wheat in storage,
normally, most of the time,

00:56:52.126 --> 00:56:57.662
this relation should hold.
The price of the futures

00:56:57.662 --> 00:57:02.933
contract should equal the spot
price times one plus the

00:57:02.933 --> 00:57:07.130
interest rate,
between now and delivery.

00:57:07.130 --> 00:57:11.373
That means that if,
say interest rates are 5% a

00:57:11.373 --> 00:57:16.723
year and the delivery is in six
months, then this should be

00:57:16.723 --> 00:57:20.957
.025--half of a year.
I want to--it's not annual

00:57:20.957 --> 00:57:23.727
interest rate;
it's the interest rate until

00:57:23.727 --> 00:57:26.397
delivery.
If it's a third of a year,

00:57:26.397 --> 00:57:30.312
you divide by whatever
the--it's the interest from

00:57:30.312 --> 00:57:35.156
today until delivery date.
S is the cost of storage

00:57:35.156 --> 00:57:38.090
from today until the delivery
date.

00:57:38.090 --> 00:57:47.340
This should hold normally all
the time and why is that?

00:57:47.340 --> 00:57:51.579
Because if I'm running a
warehouse storing grain,

00:57:51.579 --> 00:57:56.790
I can either sell at the spot
price or I I can always unload

00:57:56.790 --> 00:58:02.178
my warehouse and sell it today
or I can wait and deliver it in

00:58:02.178 --> 00:58:05.800
the future at the futures
contract.

00:58:05.800 --> 00:58:10.973
Today, as a warehouse,
I'm losing money because of the

00:58:10.973 --> 00:58:14.841
cost of storage.
I have to pay insurance and I

00:58:14.841 --> 00:58:18.772
have to do other things that
maintain the quality of my

00:58:18.772 --> 00:58:22.064
storage and that's S.
On top of that,

00:58:22.064 --> 00:58:25.858
I'm losing on interest because
if I'm storing the grain,

00:58:25.858 --> 00:58:29.791
I'm not getting interest on the
money that I paid for that

00:58:29.791 --> 00:58:32.800
grain;
that's another loss to me.

00:58:32.800 --> 00:58:36.480
So, this is the break even for
storing grain.

00:58:36.480 --> 00:58:40.674
If the futures price is enough
above the spot price that it

00:58:40.674 --> 00:58:43.928
pays for my interest cost and my
storage cost,

00:58:43.928 --> 00:58:49.279
I'm making money storing grain.
If the futures price is below

00:58:49.279 --> 00:58:52.780
this, I'm not going to store
grain;

00:58:52.780 --> 00:58:55.396
I'll unload my warehouse.
Why should I store grain for

00:58:55.396 --> 00:58:58.353
another minute?
If I'm a professional warehouse

00:58:58.353 --> 00:59:02.668
offer and I see that I can make
more money by selling my grain

00:59:02.668 --> 00:59:06.992
today, then I will do it.
Conversely, if the futures

00:59:06.992 --> 00:59:12.488
price is above the spot price,
then I'm going to want to store

00:59:12.488 --> 00:59:15.458
more grain.
I'm going to go out and buy up

00:59:15.458 --> 00:59:19.159
other grain and that's going to
tend to force the spot price up.

00:59:19.159 --> 00:59:23.594
So, this relationship tends to
hold almost all the time or you

00:59:23.594 --> 00:59:28.320
might say it holds all the time,
if you interpret it correctly.

00:59:28.320 --> 00:59:32.880
Normally, the futures price is
above the cash price because

00:59:32.880 --> 00:59:37.675
interest rates are positive and
storage costs are positive and

00:59:37.675 --> 00:59:42.103
it has to be that way.
The normal course of grain

00:59:42.103 --> 00:59:47.970
prices over the harvest year is
to rise as the year progresses.

00:59:47.970 --> 00:59:52.800
It has to be that way;
the grain is cheapest right

00:59:52.800 --> 00:59:58.089
after the harvest when there's
lots of grain around and then

00:59:58.089 --> 01:00:03.557
the grain price goes up steadily
throughout the year until the

01:00:03.557 --> 01:00:07.860
new harvest comes in and then it
collapses.

01:00:07.860 --> 01:00:15.889
The price of grain over the
year is a sawtooth pattern.

01:00:15.889 --> 01:00:27.691
If there's nothing interfering
with it, the price of grain will

01:00:27.691 --> 01:00:37.590
tend to look like this and these
are the harvests.

01:00:37.590 --> 01:00:42.235
The reason the price of grain
is going up between harvests is

01:00:42.235 --> 01:00:45.099
to compensate the warehouse
owners.

01:00:45.099 --> 01:00:47.849
They're not going to do this
business if they're not getting

01:00:47.849 --> 01:00:50.179
compensated, so this is almost
like an iron law.

01:00:50.179 --> 01:00:53.881
This is going to hold,
but it doesn't necessarily hold

01:00:53.881 --> 01:00:57.861
in a given year because there
are other things that affect

01:00:57.861 --> 01:01:01.130
price.
This is what I was saying--that

01:01:01.130 --> 01:01:06.358
arbitrage enforces fair value.
There is a problem if there is

01:01:06.358 --> 01:01:09.017
no grain in storage.
For example,

01:01:09.017 --> 01:01:12.603
right at the harvest end when
the harvest is coming in,

01:01:12.603 --> 01:01:16.456
the relation between futures
and spot price can become very

01:01:16.456 --> 01:01:19.515
erratic.
The futures price can be way

01:01:19.515 --> 01:01:22.710
below the fair value;
the right hand side--spot times

01:01:22.710 --> 01:01:25.320
one plus R plus
S--is called fair value.

01:01:25.320 --> 01:01:30.929
Futures can be below fair value
and there's no way for arbitrage

01:01:30.929 --> 01:01:35.915
to make up the difference
because there's nothing--if the

01:01:35.915 --> 01:01:40.907
futures were very low,
you would want to take money

01:01:40.907 --> 01:01:46.263
out of--take grain out of
storage and sell it on the spot

01:01:46.263 --> 01:01:48.315
market.
If there is no grain in

01:01:48.315 --> 01:01:52.031
storage, you can't do that.
It sometimes happens when the

01:01:52.031 --> 01:01:56.960
grain is not in storage that the
price of the future is below

01:01:56.960 --> 01:01:59.893
fair value.
There's another interpretation

01:01:59.893 --> 01:02:01.314
of it.
People would say,

01:02:01.314 --> 01:02:04.802
well but there is still some
grain in storage--it's not gone

01:02:04.802 --> 01:02:07.801
everywhere.
So, how can it sometimes be

01:02:07.801 --> 01:02:11.340
that the futures price is below
fair value?

01:02:11.340 --> 01:02:16.745
Well, you might say--and this
is that--you could either say

01:02:16.745 --> 01:02:22.523
that sometimes the relationship
between price and fair value is

01:02:22.523 --> 01:02:27.036
violated or you could say,
no it's never violated,

01:02:27.036 --> 01:02:30.320
but sometimes the storage cost
is negative.

01:02:30.320 --> 01:02:34.663
So, we have something called a
convenience yield,

01:02:34.663 --> 01:02:37.829
which is a negative storage
cost.

01:02:37.829 --> 01:02:43.508
Suppose you are a corn merchant
and you're noting that right now

01:02:43.508 --> 01:02:47.835
the market is in
backwardation--the futures price

01:02:47.835 --> 01:02:52.577
is less than the spot price.
So, you're thinking,

01:02:52.577 --> 01:02:58.244
I want to get grain somehow and
sell it on the spot market and

01:02:58.244 --> 01:03:01.972
I'll make money.
You go around trying to find

01:03:01.972 --> 01:03:06.246
someone to sell you grain and
you find that someone has it and

01:03:06.246 --> 01:03:09.750
won't sell it to you and you
say, well why not?

01:03:09.750 --> 01:03:13.440
The guy will say,
because I need this grain.

01:03:13.440 --> 01:03:16.570
Who has grain when the market
is in backwardation?

01:03:16.570 --> 01:03:19.059
It's somebody who really needs
it.

01:03:19.059 --> 01:03:22.120
For example,
in the case of wheat,

01:03:22.120 --> 01:03:27.685
you might find that you go to
the factory that makes Wheaties

01:03:27.685 --> 01:03:31.887
and you say,
I'd like to buy your

01:03:31.887 --> 01:03:38.680
wheat--noting that the spot
price is really high.

01:03:38.680 --> 01:03:40.829
You won't tell him that;
you say, I just want to buy

01:03:40.829 --> 01:03:44.164
your wheat.
Whatever you've got,

01:03:44.164 --> 01:03:51.469
I'll buy it at the--you
shouldn't put it that way.

01:03:51.469 --> 01:03:55.937
I guess I'm saying that it's
not going to work if you do--why

01:03:55.937 --> 01:03:59.660
doesn't the Wheaties
manufacturer sell its grain on

01:03:59.660 --> 01:04:03.599
the spot market?
The reason is that they need

01:04:03.599 --> 01:04:08.847
wheat to make Wheaties and so
for them they want to have some

01:04:08.847 --> 01:04:10.776
on hand.
They might think,

01:04:10.776 --> 01:04:14.015
well if we didn't have any
storage of wheat we would be at

01:04:14.015 --> 01:04:17.368
the mercy of delivery and who
knows when--the harvest is out

01:04:17.368 --> 01:04:19.378
now,
we might not be able to get any

01:04:19.378 --> 01:04:22.279
wheat and we may have to shut
our whole factory down and tell

01:04:22.279 --> 01:04:25.864
everyone to take a day off.
That costs us a lot of money,

01:04:25.864 --> 01:04:30.060
so we really need to have wheat
in storage at the Wheaties

01:04:30.060 --> 01:04:33.380
factory.
When the market is in

01:04:33.380 --> 01:04:38.761
backwardation,
the only grain that's stored is

01:04:38.761 --> 01:04:44.739
the grain that's there for
convenience purpose.

01:04:44.739 --> 01:04:49.059
I'm just going to go through
the example that Holbrook

01:04:49.059 --> 01:04:52.889
Working gives in his reading,
which you have.

01:04:52.889 --> 01:04:57.321
Back then, there was a number
two hard winter wheat Kansas

01:04:57.321 --> 01:05:00.120
City future--maybe there still
is;

01:05:00.120 --> 01:05:06.148
I don't know, but not at CBOT.
We're going to do this 1956 or

01:05:06.148 --> 01:05:11.868
1957 story--I have it here.
Hard wheat is used for bread,

01:05:11.868 --> 01:05:14.800
soft wheat for--remember,
this a cooking tip.

01:05:14.800 --> 01:05:20.524
You can buy bread flour at the
grocery store and you can buy

01:05:20.524 --> 01:05:23.920
cake flour and they're
different.

01:05:23.920 --> 01:05:28.834
Holbrook Working is just
talking about what happens in a

01:05:28.834 --> 01:05:32.139
typical year for hard winter
wheat.

01:05:32.139 --> 01:05:38.528
So, we're starting out now with
July 2, typical year,

01:05:38.528 --> 01:05:44.469
spot wheat was $2.29 a bushel;
that's the price on July 2.

01:05:44.469 --> 01:05:49.238
The September future is $2.32 a
bushel, so the difference

01:05:49.238 --> 01:05:53.580
between the future and the spot
is called the basis,

01:05:53.580 --> 01:05:57.875
which is $.03 a bushel.
Another term is spot premium,

01:05:57.875 --> 01:06:01.728
but that would be minus $.03,
but that's--let's just talk

01:06:01.728 --> 01:06:05.015
about basis.
The basis is the futures price

01:06:05.015 --> 01:06:11.599
minus the spot price.
This is just a typical story.

01:06:11.599 --> 01:06:13.959
So, the futures price is
selling for higher,

01:06:13.959 --> 01:06:16.154
as it should be,
because between July and

01:06:16.154 --> 01:06:19.949
September, this is winter wheat.
The harvest is recently in;

01:06:19.949 --> 01:06:24.160
the harvest came in in May and
so this is when there's a lot in

01:06:24.160 --> 01:06:28.506
storage and we really should see
the futures price above the spot

01:06:28.506 --> 01:06:33.848
price and indeed we do.
This spot premium is the profit

01:06:33.848 --> 01:06:37.809
that is offered to the
warehouser.

01:06:37.809 --> 01:06:40.364
The warehouser looks at
this--or the basis--the

01:06:40.364 --> 01:06:43.363
warehouser--people in the
warehouse business are always

01:06:43.363 --> 01:06:46.362
watching this every day and
they're looking always at a

01:06:46.362 --> 01:06:48.639
basis of $.03 and they're
thinking,

01:06:48.639 --> 01:06:51.280
are we going to make money on
that, because they have costs.

01:06:51.280 --> 01:06:54.940
But, this is how much more they
can sell it in the future than

01:06:54.940 --> 01:06:58.119
they can sell it today,
so they're comparing the basis

01:06:58.119 --> 01:07:00.688
with their costs;
they do that all the time in

01:07:00.688 --> 01:07:03.524
the warehouse business.
Now, September 4--now it's

01:07:03.524 --> 01:07:06.030
still--remember,
the harvest was May;

01:07:06.030 --> 01:07:07.690
we're not anywhere near the
harvest.

01:07:07.690 --> 01:07:12.961
Now, we still have a basis,
but now the basis has gotten

01:07:12.961 --> 01:07:15.309
smaller;
this is what happens.

01:07:15.309 --> 01:07:18.869
So, the warehouse operator is
starting to feel uncomfortable.

01:07:18.869 --> 01:07:22.269
I was doing really well in
July--I had a basis of 3.

01:07:22.269 --> 01:07:26.083
Now the basis is down to 1,
so it's getting kind of iffy

01:07:26.083 --> 01:07:28.510
for me--whether I can make
money.

01:07:28.510 --> 01:07:31.636
Maybe I should sell.
So, they're always watching

01:07:31.636 --> 01:07:34.260
these markets and thinking about
that.

01:07:38.590 --> 01:07:42.247
I'm sorry, I take that back;
I forgot, this is both the

01:07:42.247 --> 01:07:45.441
September future.
So, the basis should get

01:07:45.441 --> 01:07:50.302
smaller because we're getting
closer to the expiration date

01:07:50.302 --> 01:07:53.990
because now it's only one-month
interest.

01:07:53.990 --> 01:07:57.590
Well actually, it's even less;
we're almost expiring;

01:07:57.590 --> 01:08:00.170
I wasn't thinking when I first
saw that.

01:08:00.170 --> 01:08:05.689
The basis should shrink to zero
as the time--as you approach the

01:08:05.689 --> 01:08:10.457
expiration of the contract.
Someone in a warehouse who's

01:08:10.457 --> 01:08:15.308
worried about the fluctuation in
the grain will sell it in the

01:08:15.308 --> 01:08:19.842
futures market and then expect
to get the basis because it

01:08:19.842 --> 01:08:23.739
doesn't matter what the price of
grain does;

01:08:23.739 --> 01:08:26.930
the spot and the futures price
should converge.

01:08:26.930 --> 01:08:31.356
The basis should go to zero and
the $.03 a bushel is the profit

01:08:31.356 --> 01:08:34.069
that they make on the futures
trade.

01:08:34.069 --> 01:08:38.481
It's riskless for them at the
warehouse because they're

01:08:38.481 --> 01:08:43.627
hedging the price risk and then
it becomes a nice clean and easy

01:08:43.627 --> 01:08:46.699
business.
So, I'm looking in July 2 to

01:08:46.699 --> 01:08:49.569
see what are my costs at the
warehouse.

01:08:49.569 --> 01:08:53.692
I'm looking at this basis and I
think if I can keep my costs

01:08:53.692 --> 01:08:56.736
under $.03 a bushel,
including interest,

01:08:56.736 --> 01:09:01.651
then I will make money because
this basis is converging to zero

01:09:01.651 --> 01:09:06.328
at the end for sure--or the
stock premium will go from minus

01:09:06.328 --> 01:09:09.420
3 to 0--so this is a normal
month.

01:09:09.420 --> 01:09:13.069
Some months storing grain had
this basis of $.03 a bushel and

01:09:13.069 --> 01:09:16.536
is doing business as usual,
storing for less than that and

01:09:16.536 --> 01:09:18.816
making money.
If not less than that,

01:09:18.816 --> 01:09:23.405
then get out of it.
Then, continuing through the

01:09:23.405 --> 01:09:29.821
year--now they roll into
December futures because I'm

01:09:29.821 --> 01:09:34.220
still storing grain;
I do this all year.

01:09:34.220 --> 01:09:38.024
I'm trading in the nearest
month contract because that's

01:09:38.024 --> 01:09:42.520
where the open interest is and
that's where all the trading is.

01:09:42.520 --> 01:09:46.698
So, as soon the September
contract expires,

01:09:46.698 --> 01:09:50.180
I don't actually want to
deliver.

01:09:50.180 --> 01:09:53.840
I'll sell out and I'll make the
profit, which is the change in

01:09:53.840 --> 01:09:56.324
basis.
Now, when it comes to--now,

01:09:56.324 --> 01:09:59.517
September 4,
I've made that profit of $.02 a

01:09:59.517 --> 01:10:02.293
bushel.
The difference between the $.03

01:10:02.293 --> 01:10:06.229
a bushel basis and the $.01 and
now I start a new contract.

01:10:06.229 --> 01:10:09.880
Now, because September is
expiring, I move in.

01:10:09.880 --> 01:10:13.897
I roll over into the December
contract and I'm just going to

01:10:13.897 --> 01:10:17.569
do this every contract.
Every three months I'm going to

01:10:17.569 --> 01:10:19.729
roll over into the next
contract.

01:10:19.729 --> 01:10:23.000
In this case--I didn't put the
basis;

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:27.472
the basis was $.0575 a bushel.
So now, it's looking even

01:10:27.472 --> 01:10:30.329
better here in September.
I mean, it jumps around;

01:10:30.329 --> 01:10:32.919
the basis jumps around with
market conditions,

01:10:32.919 --> 01:10:35.796
but it's looking good now
because I have a basis of

01:10:35.796 --> 01:10:39.669
$.0575.
So, I'll sell my grain again on

01:10:39.669 --> 01:10:45.940
a futures contract and then I
will close it out December when

01:10:45.940 --> 01:10:51.665
the--this is December 1 now.
Now the price of wheat has gone

01:10:51.665 --> 01:10:56.396
up a lot from $2.38 to $2.52,
but you know it's not going to

01:10:56.396 --> 01:10:59.595
be profit for me.
I'm not--I hedged it,

01:10:59.595 --> 01:11:03.924
but I'll make the--for me,
the profit is the change in the

01:11:03.924 --> 01:11:07.096
spot premium.
So, I made $.0575 a bushel

01:11:07.096 --> 01:11:09.410
minus my costs.
I'll just stop;

01:11:09.410 --> 01:11:13.370
I know I'm running out of time.
What happens at harvest?

01:11:13.370 --> 01:11:17.202
I'm doing this all year.
Finally on May--this is--the

01:11:17.202 --> 01:11:20.789
new harvest is coming in and
look what happens;

01:11:20.789 --> 01:11:26.010
now this market is suddenly in
backwardation.

01:11:26.010 --> 01:11:29.908
Now, look what's happening;
the spot premium is $.18 a

01:11:29.908 --> 01:11:32.590
bushel;
the basis is minus 18.

01:11:32.590 --> 01:11:36.521
If I hold on--if I rolled into
July futures and hold on,

01:11:36.521 --> 01:11:40.810
I'm going to lose really big
time, so I'm out--I'm out of the

01:11:40.810 --> 01:11:43.369
business.
We sell off everything in the

01:11:43.369 --> 01:11:47.064
warehouse and we're done.
This is the process by which

01:11:47.064 --> 01:11:51.931
warehousing is optimized and we
get grain smoothly through the

01:11:51.931 --> 01:11:54.728
year,
but it's the basic principle

01:11:54.728 --> 01:11:58.814
that we'll see in the next
lecture--extends as well to

01:11:58.814 --> 01:12:01.590
other kinds of financial
futures.

01:12:01.590 --> 01:12:05.563
Next period,
we're going to talk about other

01:12:05.563 --> 01:12:10.000
kinds of futures,
including financial futures.

